      "question": "How do you handle optionals safely? When do you reach for `if let` vs `guard let`, and why is force-unwrap a code smell?",
      "answer": "An optional is just an enum (`.some`/`.none`) that makes \"absence\" explicit in the type system, so the compiler forces you to deal with `nil` instead of crashing at runtime.\n\nMy toolkit:\n\n- `guard let x else { return }` for **early-exit** unwrapping — it keeps `x` in scope for the rest of the function and flattens the happy path, so I reach for it at the top of a method.\n- `if let x` (shorthand) when the value is only needed inside a **narrow branch**.\n- `??` to supply a default (`name ?? \"Guest\"`), and optional chaining (`user?.profile?.avatarURL`) to short-circuit a whole chain to `nil` instead of nesting checks.\n\n- Red flag: force-unwrapping (`!`) any value that came from the network or a user. It asserts \"never nil\" and **traps** if you're wrong — it trades a compile-time guarantee for a runtime crash. I only allow it for genuine programmer-error invariants (e.g. a hardcoded `URL(string:)!`).\n\n**I treat every optional as a real branch in my logic, not a checkbox to silence the compiler.**",
