      "answer": "Structs are **value types**: assigning or passing one copies it, so each holder gets an independent instance with no shared identity. Classes are **reference types**: holders share one heap instance, and they add inheritance, identity (`===`), and deinitializers.\n\nApple's guidance, which I follow: **default to a struct**, reach for a class only when you need reference semantics — shared mutable state, identity, inheritance, or Objective-C / `NSObject` interop.\n\nValue semantics kill a class of aliasing bugs: a struct can't be mutated out from under you. The nuance is **copy-on-write** — `Array`, `String`, and `Dictionary` are structs but only copy their backing storage on mutation, so you get value semantics without copying on every pass. Also, `let` on a struct freezes all its stored properties, whereas `let` on a class only freezes the reference, not the object's `var` properties.\n\n**I default to structs and only reach for a class when I need shared identity or inheritance — that default alone prevents a whole class of aliasing bugs.**",
