      "answer": "A Swift enum can attach a **different payload to each case**, so it models a value that is exactly one of several mutually exclusive shapes — and the compiler forces you to handle each. This is the idiomatic way to make illegal states unrepresentable.\n\nThe canonical example is a load state:\n\n- `enum LoadState { case idle; case loading; case loaded([Item]); case failed(Error) }`\n\nNow `loaded` carries its items and `failed` carries its error, but you can't have items *and* an error at once — the type makes that impossible. You destructure with a `switch` and binding: `case .loaded(let items):`. `Optional` and `Result<Success, Failure>` are themselves just enums with associated values.\n\nThe nuance: an exhaustive `switch` turns adding a new case into a **compile error** at every call site — exactly the safety net you want as the model grows, far better than a struct of optional fields where invalid combinations slip through.\n\n**I model state as an enum with associated values so illegal states are unrepresentable, not just unlikely.**",
