      "question": "What is ARC, and how does it differ from a tracing garbage collector?",
      "answer": "**ARC** (Automatic Reference Counting) is a compile-time mechanism: the Swift compiler inserts `retain`/`release` calls so a class instance is deallocated the instant its strong reference count hits zero. There is no runtime collector scanning the heap.\n\nA tracing GC (JVM, Go) runs periodically, walks the object graph from roots to find what's reachable, and frees the rest on its own schedule.\n\nKey differences:\n- **Determinism:** ARC frees objects immediately and predictably, so `deinit` runs at a known point; a tracing GC frees later, non-deterministically.\n- **Pauses vs overhead:** ARC has no stop-the-world pause, but pays for atomic retain/release traffic on every ownership change.\n- **Cycles:** a tracing GC reclaims reference cycles automatically; ARC cannot, so you break them with `weak`/`unowned`.\n\nARC governs only reference types (classes, and the boxed storage behind closures), not value types like structs and enums.\n\n**ARC trades a tracing collector's pause for deterministic, immediate deallocation — the price is atomic retain/release traffic and manual cycle-breaking.**",
