      "question": "Loading full-resolution images into thumbnails tanks scroll performance and memory. What's actually going wrong and how do you fix it?",
      "answer": "A `UIImage` is compressed on disk but **decoded** into an uncompressed bitmap in memory — roughly width x height x 4 bytes — so a 4000x3000 photo costs ~48MB no matter the 100pt thumbnail it lands in. Decode also happens lazily on the main thread at draw time, which is what stalls the scroll.\n\n- Red flag: assuming a small `UIImageView` frame limits memory cost. `UIImage` decodes to full resolution regardless of the display size — resizing the frame does nothing for the bitmap already in RAM.\n\nThe fix is **downsampling**: `CGImageSourceCreateThumbnailAtIndex` with `kCGImageSourceThumbnailMaxPixelSize` (target size in pixels) plus `kCGImageSourceCreateThumbnailFromImageAlways`, decoding straight to the size you need off the main thread. The senior nuance is to force-decode ahead of display so the main thread never decodes mid-scroll, and to cap an `NSCache` so the bitmap cache stays inside the memory budget.\n\n**Downsampling at decode time, not display time, is what actually caps memory.**",
