      "question": "A SwiftUI screen re-renders far more than expected. How does body re-evaluation work and how do you minimize it?",
      "answer": "SwiftUI re-invokes a view's `body` when a dependency it reads changes. Re-running `body` is itself cheap; the cost is when it cascades into child re-evaluation and layout.\n\nTechniques:\n- **Scope state narrowly.** Put `@State` on the smallest subview that needs it; hoisting state too high is the most common cause of over-rendering.\n- **Adopt Observation** (`@Observable`, iOS 17+): views re-render only when the **specific properties they actually read** change, versus `ObservableObject` where any `@Published` mutation invalidates every observer.\n- **Avoid minting fresh reference identities or closures in `body`**, and keep value types `Equatable` so SwiftUI can skip redundant diffs.\n\nThe senior tell is confirming with `Self._printChanges()` (or the SwiftUI Instrument) to see *what* invalidated, instead of scattering `EquatableView` blindly.\n\n**I confirm what invalidated with `Self._printChanges()` before I reach for `EquatableView` — optimizing the wrong dependency just moves the re-render, it doesn't remove it.**",
